'''Preferentialism''' is a [[philosophical movement]] which began in [[Paris]] in the early 1990s. In direct opposition to the relativism of [[Existentialism]], Preferentialism stresses [[Objectivity (philosophy)|objectivity]] and [[natural law]] principles, applying the latter to [[epistemology]] as well as to [[morality]] and [[ethics]].<ref>Mamas, D. L., Phys. Essays 27, 515 (2014) http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2014PhyEs..27..515M</ref> Preferentialism states that there are certain absolute ''preferential'' frames of reference which are preferred by nature, in opposition to the [[individualism|individualistic]] relativism of Existentialism.<ref>Mamas, D. L., Phys. Essays 27, 515 (2014).</ref> Preferentialism is a general philosophical concept whereby it is the decisive criterion of nature which imposes preferential bases of reference in all major areas of philosophy.
Preferentialism has application in the social sciences.<ref>Rønnow-Rasmussen, T., Personal Value. Oxford: Oxford University Press (2011).</ref> <ref> Ronnow-Rasmussen, T., http://www.lunduniversity.lu.se/lup/publication/793456 </ref>
A comparison of Preferentialism vis-à-vis Existentialism is analyzed in the philosophy journal ''Hildegarde''<ref>Popieul, A., ''Hildegarde'' 5, 11-18 (2016) https://issuu.com/hildegardefanzine/docs/hildegarde_novembre_16_1.8 </ref>
